    <h2>Types of Scholarships You Should Know</h2>
    <p>Scholarships come in many forms, and understanding the different types helps you target your search effectively. Most students focus exclusively on merit-based academic scholarships, but the scholarship landscape is far broader than GPA and test scores alone.</p>
    <p><strong>Merit-based scholarships</strong> reward academic achievement, typically requiring a minimum GPA of 3.0 or higher and strong standardized test scores. These are among the most competitive awards, often offered directly by colleges as part of their admissions packages. National merit scholarships, institutional presidential scholarships, and dean's scholarships all fall into this category.</p>
    <p><strong>Need-based scholarships</strong> are awarded based on demonstrated financial need, usually determined by FAFSA data or a separate application form. These scholarships aim to make college accessible for students from lower-income families. Many private foundations, community organizations, and colleges themselves offer need-based awards that supplement federal and state financial aid.</p>
    <p><strong>Athletic scholarships</strong> are offered by colleges to recruit talented athletes. NCAA Division I and II schools offer athletic scholarships, while Division III schools do not. The number of full-ride athletic scholarships is limited — only about 2 percent of high school athletes receive them — but partial athletic awards are more common and can still cover a significant portion of costs.</p>
    <p><strong>Demographic scholarships</strong> target students from specific backgrounds, including scholarships for underrepresented minorities, women in STEM fields, first-generation college students, LGBTQ students, students with disabilities, and students from specific geographic regions or states. Organizations like the Hispanic Scholarship Fund, United Negro College Fund, and American Indian College Fund administer major scholarship programs in this category.</p>
    <p><strong>Community and civic scholarships</strong> reward students who demonstrate strong community involvement, volunteer work, or leadership. Service organizations like Rotary, Kiwanis, Elks, and Lions clubs frequently sponsor scholarships for students in their communities. These local awards often have smaller applicant pools, making them easier to win.</p>
    <p><strong>Employer-sponsored scholarships</strong> are offered by companies to employees' children or to students pursuing careers in the company's industry. Many large corporations — including Walmart, Google, Coca-Cola, and Toyota — sponsor scholarship programs. Some are restricted to employees' families, while others are open to any qualifying student.</p>
    <p>The most successful scholarship seekers apply across multiple categories rather than limiting themselves to one type. A student with a 3.5 GPA, moderate financial need, and strong community service involvement might qualify for scholarships in at least four of these categories simultaneously.</p>

    <h2>Where to Search for Scholarships</h2>
